<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-617-803  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 617 803.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Oct 29 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Australia: MacDonalds adopts new Xenix payroll system.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Zucker, Paul.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   MacDonald's Corp. (Data processing).andO;Topic:     AustraliaPayrollAccountingRestaurant BusinessElectronic Data Processing.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>AUSTRALIA: MACDONALDS ADOPTS NEW XENIX PAYROLL SYSTEM SYDNEY, AUSTRALIA, 1990OCT 29 (NB) -- US fast-food giant MacDonalds has finally given-up manualtimekeeping methods in its Australian stores.andP;  Each outlet will have a Xenix-based, dedicated payroll 386sx PC with automatic communications to the headoffice.andM;The $500,000 system was developed in Australia by a single consultant, and isexpected to save each store manager 13 hours per week, and head officeaccounting staff, 75 hours per week.andP;  It is also expected to cut employeequeries to around five percent of existing levels.andM;Developed by John Hartley, MACS (managers administrative control system) issaid to require next to no expertise from the store managers, most of whomhave no computer training.andP;  The next phase of the system will be theintegration of MacDonalds US-sourced inventory, sales and cash controlsystem, already in 2000 sites internationally.andP;  If MACS is as successful asit promises, it may be adopted by US MacDonalds stores.andM;(Paul Zucker/19901029)</TEXT></DOC>